<subSubSection pageId="208" pageNumber="487" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6707632" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6707632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6707632/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="208" pageNumber="487" targetBox="[172,764,1096,1510]" targetPageId="208">
<paragraph blockId="208.[787,1378,1088,1511]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[787,963,1246,1275]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">Distribution.</emphasis>
W &amp; N Venezuela (Andes and disjunct in mountain ranges in the states of Falcon and Yaracuy and in the 
<taxonomicName authority="de" box="[788,973,1364,1393]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Chrysobalanaceae" genus="Cordillera" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="208" pageNumber="497" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Cordillera de</taxonomicName>
la Costa).
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="208" pageNumber="487" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="208.[787,1378,1088,1511]" lastBlockId="208.[172,1378,1518,2103]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[787,1024,1399,1432]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 121-150 mm, tail 123-165 mm, ear 18-20 mm, hindfoot 26-30 mm; weight 41-75 g. Medium-sized rat with pelage soft and dense, bright chestnut brown on dorsum and white tipped over dark slate hair bases below. Tail is sometimes reddish rather than dark, terminating in pencil of hairs 10-15 mm long. Ears are large, well-haired, and dark. Hindfeet have welldefined dark patches over metatarsals; sides of metatarsal part and toes yellowish are white.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="208" pageNumber="487" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="208.[172,1378,1518,2103]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[174,284,1675,1708]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">Habitat.</emphasis>
Cloud forests, primary and secondary evergreen forests, and coffee plantations at elevations mostly above 2000 m. Charming Climbing Rats have been caught among forest orchids, in trees and vines, under bushes, and on rock ledges.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[174,674,1793,1826]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="208.[172,1378,1518,2103]" box="[174,674,1793,1826]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[174,435,1793,1826]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
No information.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="208" pageNumber="487" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="208.[172,1378,1518,2103]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[174,308,1837,1866]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">Breeding.</emphasis>
Little is knwon, but one female Charming Climbing Rat had two embryos in the wet season (May-October).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="208" pageNumber="487" type="activity">
<paragraph blockId="208.[172,1378,1518,2103]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[172,408,1911,1944]" pageId="208" pageNumber="487">Activity patterns.</emphasis>
The Charming Climbing Rat is terrestrial and arboreal and is active at night.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
